                                          Stateful & Stateless Architecture


Session Data/State:- Data that represents user's session on wed.
                         -> Indentify a user
                         -> Authenticate the user

User->A
                   web-server-1
                    state info. of user-A
-----------------------------------------------------------------
User->B     
               web-server-2
               state-info of user-B


Stateless Web                                   Stateful web
- Does not remember client data                 - Remember client data.
- Does not store state information              - stores state information
- Simple, robust                                - overhead, not simple

Disadvantages:

❌ Hard to scale (needs sticky sessions)

❌ Server dependency

❌ Failures lose session

❌ Load balancer complexity

✅ Advantages:

✅ Faster (no need to fetch session repeatedly)

✅ Simple logic (session already available)

                              
1. Stateful Architecture (With Load Balancer):-
            Users
             |
        Load Balancer
         /        \
   Web Server 1   Web Server 2
   (User A state) (User B state)

Load balancer must send the same user to same server


2. Stateless Architecture (Modern Approach):-
              Users
                |
          Load Balancer
        /      |      \
   Server1  Server2  Server3
        \      |      /
          Shared Cache / DB

How it works:

Any request → Any server

No session stored in server

Data stored in:

- Cache (Redis)

- Database

Benefits:

->Easy scaling 

->Fault tolerant

->No sticky session needed


